A. What exactly is a creature attacking you with?<br>
B. What are the actually effects, duration or damage range?<br>
C. How do Ferocity and Deathblow stats figure in?<br>
<br>
Just curious ......<img border=0 src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/eyes.gif" /> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000028><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub60.ezboard.com/bcreaturehandlersofswg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=encymnon>Encymnon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#70DB93>(11/12/03 8:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub60.ezboard.com/fcreaturehandlersofswgfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=137.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Pet Statistics</span><hr size=1> I am a bit curious on some of these as well<br>
<br>
I dont do much PVP, so i cant comment on the deathblowing (since in PVE everything gets deathblown)<br>
<br>
As for Special protection, effectiveness and vulnerability, here is how i see it from testing different pets against different weapon damage and opponents (dueling friends):<br>
<br>
1. Vulnerability is thier weakness to a type of damage - if the have Acid listed under their vulnerability, then a DX2 pistol will work well against them. <br>
<br>
2. Special protection is their resistances to certain things. If they have Acid X% listed in special protection, then a DX2 might not be the best choice of weapon.<br>
<br>
3. Effectiveness -- here is where i am unsure. Is it how effective that type of damage is against them? Or is it how effective they are against someone with that type of protection. If the former, then what is the difference between it and Special Protection?<br>
<br>
As i understand it, all pets do Restraint damage (not heat or elictricity or kinetic). They may also do additional damage via a special attack (e.g. a squirt of acid, or some type of poison)., but their main "melee" attack is always Restraint.<br>
<br>
Ferocity: What does it do? Again, i am unsure. However, my best guess is that it makes pets less likely to be intimidated into turning and running from whatever they are fighting when they get a bit hurt. Try fighting with a giant sand beetle (CL 30) and then try fighting with a Graul (CL 30) -- bet the Graul stays in the fight without turning tail and retreating after it gets hit a few times. Grauls - Ferocious. Beetles - Not.<br>
<br>
But, this may be conjecture. I have no hard data that this is the case -- this is more just from obsevation and experience...<br>
<br>
hpe that all helps, and hope someone with more info will follow this up further, as i would love to know more :) <p>Bards - the &quot;clothing-optional&quot; class.<br>
